[1] Colombia (Valle del Cauca)
Date: Wed 27 Jan 2010
Source: El Pais [in Spanish, trans & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.elpais.com.co/paisonline/calionline/notas/Enero252010/cali1.html>


Cali is one of the cities most affected by dengue. The latest reports
by the Secretariat of Health indicate that in the course of the year
[2010], there have now been 218 cases of classical dengue registered,
a number 4 times higher than the same period in 2009, when only 54
cases were registered.

But most worrying is that in the 1st 24 days of 2010, in the
University del Valle Hospital (UVH), 4 dengue deaths have been
registered. The UVH infectious disease physician, Yolanda Caicedo,
explained that these deaths relate to patients who arrive at the
hospital in very serious condition because they have not received
adequate attention in other [health] centers. Because of this, the
recommendation for physicians is that when they see patients in bad
[condition], it is better to immediately hospitalize them and not
confuse dengue with a simple viral infection.

This year [2010], there are 22 DHF cases in the Valle capital which
relate to patients with hemorrhage and being in serious condition.

The Secretary of Health, Alejandro Varela, stated that Cali, together
with Palmira [near Cali] and Baranquilla [on the Caribbean coast],
have been the cities most affected by dengue outbreaks, since they
have tropical climates and are near rivers [dengue mosquitoes do not
breed in rivers. - Mod.JW]. [He] reminded us at the time that they are
aware of the risk that the city faces, and for that reason are
increasing control [measures], mainly [focusing] on breeding sites of
the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_ that causes dengue [transmits dengue
viruses]. Homes must avoid stored water, where the mosquitoes are
[breeding], and be alert for symptoms such as fever, body ache,
vomiting, loss of appetite, among others.

Up to now, Commune 17 in Cali (south) is the [area] most affected by
this disease; this year [2010], there are 25 cases.

Meanwhile, in Palmira there is a considerable threat, since there is
now a death registered from [dengue]. On 5 Jan [2010], a girl of 4
years died of DHF.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[The total numbers of classical dengue cases through 27 January in
this report, 218, are less than those reported through 21 January, 282
(see ProMED archive no. 20100125.0277). This discrepancy may be due to
inclusion of DHF cases in the previous week's total or to inclusion of
cases from a larger geographic area. In any case, with 22 cases of DHF
& 4 deaths already -- an extraordinarily high rate (10 per cent) --
Cali is going through a serious dengue outbreak currently. During
2009, through epidemiological week 46, Colombia reported to PAHO a DHF
rate of 14 per cent, double that of any other country in the Americas
except Suriname, but did not identify what the epidemic strain was.

A map showing the location of the Department of Valle del Cauca in
western Colombia can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/txu-oclc-256488229-colombia_pol_2008.jpg>. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Colombia can be accessed at <http://healthmap.org/r/013a>. -
Mod.TY/JW]

